Polynomial division shows us that
$\frac{x^3 + x^2}{x^2 + 1} = (x+1) + \frac{-x-1}{x^2 + 1}$.
Therefore\\\\ \begin{align*}
\frac{x^3 + x^2}{x^2 + 1} - (x+1) &= \frac{-x-1}{x^2 + 1}
\\ \lim_{x \to \pm\infty} [f(x) - (x+1)] &= \lim_{x \to \pm\infty} \frac{-x-1}{x^2 + 1}
\\ \lim_{x \to \pm\infty} [f(x) - (x+1)] &= 0\end{align*}

Hence $\displaystyle {\color{blue} y = x +1}$ is a slant asymptote of
$\displaystyle f(x)$.
